The antiphospholipid antibody syndrome (APS) is a
clinical-pathologic correlation that includes a
clinical event (e.g. arterial or venous thrombosis,
pregnancy morbidity) and persistent positive
antiphospholipid antibodies (IgM or IgG ACA >40
MPL/GPL-U/mL, IgM or IgG anti-b2GPI antibodies or a
lupus anticoagulant). International consensus
guidelines for APS suggest waiting at least 12 weeks
before retesting to confirm antibody persistence. The
Systemic Lupus International Collaborating Clinics
immunological classification criteria for systemic
lupus erythematosus (SLE) include testing for isotype
IgA, which has yet to be incorporated into APS
criteria. Low level antiphospholipid antibodies may
sometimes be detected in the setting of infection,
drug therapy or aging.
